-led work. Essays feature the perspectives of three students and professors originally involved in the project, reflecting on their learning and exploring the works they selected for the original exhibition. The essays lead to a beautifully illustrated catalogue of the original student designs. Reproduced in full color and with the accompanying poems in both their original language and a translation, this catalogue commemorates the incredible creative spirit of the project and provides a new way of contemplating these great poetic works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aMultilingualismxStudy and teaching (Higher)zNew JerseyzNew Brunswick. 0aPolitical poetryvExhibitions. 0aPosters, AmericanzNew JerseyzNew BrunswickvExhibitions. 0aSocial problemsvPostersvExhibitions. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  acreative graphic design, graphic design, poetry, Rutgers Mason Gross School of the Arts, graphic design exhibition, Rutgers University, college art, artistic endeavors, celebrating diversity, diversity, pedagogy, language study, humanities pedagogy, poems, college student art, college exhibits, Rutgers admissions, Rutgers alumni, Mason Gross School of the Arts, arts students, Celebration of Language, Language Art and Learning, Arts and Media.1 aAkin, Atif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkin, Atif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornilliat, Francois, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornilliat, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLosSantos, Jenevieve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLosSantos, Jenevieve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDeleger, Ouafaa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo